06389nam a22007695i 9780887558566DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20202020xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808875585667 a10.1515/97808875585662doi  a(DE-B1597)664564  a(OCoLC)1134765746  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxcCA 4aE78.C2bP38 2020 7aPOL0450002bisacsh04a971.004/9722300aPathways of Reconciliation :bIndigenous and Settler Approaches to Implementing the TRC's Calls to Action /ced. by Paulette Regan, Aimée Craft. 1aWinnipeg, Manitoba : bUniversity of Manitoba Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPerceptions on Truth and Reconciliation ;v200tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tReframing -- tPaved with Comfortable Intentions -- tPerceptions on Truth and Reconciliation -- tMonitoring that Reconciles -- tA Move to Distract -- tLearning and Healing -- tTeaching Truth Before Reconciliation -- tLearning and Reconciliation for the Collaborative Governance of Forestland in Northwestern Ontario, Canada -- tResearching -- tWhat Does Reconciliation Mean to Newcomers Post-Trc? -- tHealing from Residential School Experiences -- tLiving -- tBending to the Prevailing Wind -- tHow Do I Reconcile Child and Family Services’ Practice of Cultural Genocide with my Own Practice as a Cfs Social Worker? -- tRepatriation, Reconciliation, and Refiguring Relationships -- tConclusion -- tAcknowledgements -- tBibliography -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince the Truth and Reconciliation Commission released its Calls to Action in June 2015, governments, churches, non-profit, professional and community organizations, corporations, schools and universities, clubs and individuals have asked: “How can I/we participate in reconciliation?" Recognizing that reconciliation is not only an ultimate goal, but a decolonizing process of journeying in ways that embody everyday acts of resistance, resurgence, and solidarity, coupled with renewed commitments to justice, dialogue, and relationship-building, Pathways of Reconciliation helps readers find their way forward. The essays in Pathways of Reconciliation address the themes of reframing, learning and healing, researching, and living. They engage with different approaches to reconciliation (within a variety of reconciliation frameworks, either explicit or implicit) and illustrate the complexities of the reconciliation process itself. They canvass multiple and varied pathways of reconciliation, from Indigenous and non-Indigenous perspectives, reflecting a diversity of approaches to the mandate given to all Canadians by the TRC with its Calls to Action. Together the authors—academics, practitioners, students and ordinary citizens—demonstrate the importance of trying and learning from new and creative approaches to thinking about and practicing reconciliation and reflect on what they have learned from their attempts (both successful and less successful) in the process.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIndigenous peoplesxAbuse ofzCanada. 0aReconciliation. 0aTruth commissionszCanada. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Colonialism & Post-Colonialism.2bisacsh1 aBush, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarr, Tracey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChartier, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClarke, Mary Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCraft, Aimée, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCraft, Aimée, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 a